Method Chaining in Java

Method chaining is a programming technique where multiple methods are called one after another in a single statement.

👉 The result of one method becomes the object on which the next method is called.

Basic Idea

Instead of writing:

Stream<String> stream = list.stream();

stream = stream.filter(s -> s.length() > 5);

stream = stream.map(String::toUpperCase);

stream.forEach(System.out::println);

We can write:

list.stream()
    .filter(s -> s.length() > 5)
    .map(String::toUpperCase)
    .forEach(System.out::println);

👉 This is called method chaining.

Why Does It Work?

Method chaining works because most methods return an object.

Example:

stream.filter(...)

returns:

Stream<T>

Then you can immediately call another method:

stream.filter(...)
      .map(...)

because map() is also a method of Stream.

Example Step by Step
List<String> fruits = List.of(
        "apple",
        "banana",
        "orange"
);

fruits.stream()
      .filter(fruit -> fruit.length() > 5)
      .map(String::toUpperCase)
      .sorted()
      .forEach(System.out::println);

Execution:

Create a stream.
Keep only words with more than 5 letters.
Convert them to uppercase.
Sort them.
Print the result.

Output:

BANANA
ORANGE
Method Chaining in Stream API

A typical stream pipeline looks like this:

Source
   ↓
Intermediate Operation
   ↓
Intermediate Operation
   ↓
Intermediate Operation
   ↓
Terminal Operation

Example:

list.stream()
    .filter(...)
    .map(...)
    .sorted()
    .forEach(...);
Intermediate Operations

These methods return another Stream, allowing the chain to continue.

Examples:

filter()
map()
sorted()
distinct()
limit()
skip()
Terminal Operations

These methods end the chain.

Examples:

forEach()
collect()
count()
reduce()
findFirst()

After a terminal operation, the stream is closed and cannot be used again.

Another Example
List<Integer> numbers =
        List.of(5, 2, 8, 1, 3);

List<Integer> result =
        numbers.stream()
               .filter(n -> n > 2)
               .sorted()
               .toList();

Execution:

5 2 8 1 3
↓
filter (>2)
↓
5 8 3
↓
sorted
↓
3 5 8
↓
toList()
Advantages

✅ Cleaner code

✅ More readable

✅ Easy to follow

✅ Less temporary variables

Common Mistakes
Calling a terminal operation too early
list.stream()
    .forEach(System.out::println)
    .filter(...); // ❌ Error

forEach() returns void, so there is no stream left to continue the chain.

Reusing a Stream
Stream<String> stream = list.stream();

stream.forEach(System.out::println);

stream.forEach(System.out::println); // ❌ Error

A stream can only be consumed once.

Real-Life Analogy

Imagine making coffee:

Coffee Beans
      ↓
Grind
      ↓
Brew
      ↓
Pour
      ↓
Drink

Each step takes the result of the previous one.

A stream pipeline works the same way.

Summary
Method chaining means calling methods one after another.
Each method returns an object that allows the next method to be called.
Stream API relies heavily on method chaining.
Intermediate operations return a Stream.
A terminal operation finishes the pipeline.
Method chaining makes code shorter, cleaner, and easier to read.
